            <p>However, the figure above is <b>more than just a replica</b> of the original -- it is <i>content-preserved</i>, meaning that it can be detached from its original creation environment without losing the ability to be repurposed. 
               When we repurpose a graphic, we perform a new analysis to create a new view that may not have been anticipated by the original author(s). 
               This empowers the audience to <i>continue the endeavor</i> to further understand or provide alternative interpretations of the material presented in the original.
            </p>

            <p>
            Using the content-preservation technique that we present in our VAST 2013 paper, audiences no longer need to take another's graphic <i>at face falue</i>; instead, 
            <i>sharing the graphic</i> is <i>sharing the data</i>.
            For example, anyone can create <a href="http://ieeevis.tw.rpi.edu/lam-2012-evaluations-7-scenarios">a replica of Lam et al.'s <i>second</i> figure</a> 
            given only the graphic for her first figure (shown above).
            </p>

            <p>If you take a peek at <a href="http://ieeevis.tw.rpi.edu/lam-2012-evaluations-7-scenarios">our replica of Figure 2</a>, you'll notice that <i>more details</i> are shown than in Figure 1 above.
               The second figure is not just a new view of the material in the first, nor is it a more abstract summary. 
               The ability to use new material is afforded by the content-preservation technique that we describe in our VAST paper.
            </p>

            <p>
            Content-preservation is a technique that can be applied to a variety of graphical formats and within a variety of graphic production environments.
            The replica above is in SVG and was created using d3.js in the browser. We created three other replicas of Lam's Figure 1 using our own VSR graphic production system.
